        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://standards.iso.org/iso/10303/-4000/tech/refdata/core_v1#a8535000-130a-0135-b552-598f1b1392ae"/>
        <dc:contributor>STEP Harmonization Team</dc:contributor>
        <dc:creator>Phil Spiby, Eurostep</dc:creator>
        <dc:date>2021-07-30</dc:date>
        <dc:source>ISO/IEC/IEEE 24748-1:2018 Systems and software engineering — Life cycle management — Part 1: Guidelines for life cycle management, Table 1</dc:source>
        <dc:type>InWork</dc:type>
        <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Life cycle stage which purpose is to store, archive or dispose of system</rdfs:comment>
        <owl:versionInfo>1</owl:versionInfo>
        <skos:changeNote>[2021-07-30] Initial definition.</skos:changeNote>
        <skos:prefLabel xml:lang="en">retirement stage</skos:prefLabel>
    </owl:NamedIndividual>
    


    <!-- http://standards.iso.org/iso/10303/-4000/tech/refdata/core_rd_v1#1d3aac2d-f22f-4d79-bab2-1f26c9aea1ff -->

    <owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="http://standards.iso.org/iso/10303/-4000/tech/refdata/core_rd_v1#1d3aac2d-f22f-4d79-bab2-1f26c9aea1ff">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://standards.iso.org/iso/10303/-4000/tech/refdata/core_v1#a8535000-130a-0135-b552-598f1b1392ae"/>
        <dc:contributor>STEP Harmonization Team</dc:contributor>
        <dc:creator>Phil Spiby, Eurostep</dc:creator>
        <dc:date>2021-07-30</dc:date>
        <dc:source>INCOSE Systems Engineering Body of Knowledge, v. 2.1, 31 October 2019 (https://www.sebokwiki.org/wiki/System_Life_Cycle_Process_Models:_Vee)</dc:source>
        <dc:type>InWork</dc:type>
        <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">user requirements analysis and agreement is part of the exploratory research stage and is critical to the development of successful systems. Without proper understanding of the user needs, any system runs the risk of being built to solve the wrong problems. The first step in the exploratory research phase is to define the user (and stakeholder) requirements and constraints. A key part of this process is to establish the feasibility of meeting the user requirements, including technology readiness assessment. As with many Systems Engineering activities this is often done iteratively, and stakeholder needs and requirements are revisited as new information becomes available</rdfs:comment>
        <owl:versionInfo>1</owl:versionInfo>
        <skos:changeNote>[2021-07-30] Initial definition.</skos:changeNote>
        <skos:prefLabel xml:lang="en">exploratory research stage</skos:prefLabel>
    </owl:NamedIndividual>
    


